\begin_layout Title
Density
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We estimate, from first principles, a common-sense result: When the density
 of backcountry travelers becomes comparable to the size of a day's potential
 avalanches, multi-party avalanche incidents become likely.
 Furthermore, the likelihood is quadratic in the density of travelers –
 twice as many parties quadruples the likelihood.
 The argument is made, with recent examples from Washington State, that
 multi-party incidents are a timely concern.
 To stimulate conversation, we enumerate a variety of untested strategies
 to mitigate the hazard.
\end_layout

