That is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{\text{accident}}=A_{\text{start-zones}}(n+A_{\text{avalanche}}n^{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or, suggestively,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{\text{accident}}=A_{\text{start-zones}}n(1+A_{\text{avalanche}}n)\label{eq:Combined Single and multi-party accident rate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the skier density, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, is small, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 is smaller still, just as 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.1)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 0.01.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is larger than 1, though, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 dominates the problem, just as 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 100.
 Okay, great; what sets the scale of "1" ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Combined Single and multi-party accident rate"

\end_inset

 holds the answer: it is the size of the day's typical avalanche that matters.
 Once 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{avalanche}n>1$
\end_inset

, inter-party incidents will dominate.
 This is a common-sense idea – once there is roughly one party per avalanche-are
a, any triggered avalanche is likely to hit another party.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, we know this to be true – in-bounds slides at ski areas are
 scary in part because the skier density is so high.
 It also suggests that inter-party incidents are likely to be a larger fraction
 of accidents involving large avalanches – another common sense idea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relationship of multi-party accident rate to avalanche size
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Quadratic Scaling"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Combined Single and multi-party accident rate"

\end_inset

 hold more for us, another common-sense result.
 If the size or likelihood of a day's avalanches is greater, we should expect
 the rate at which multi-party accidents occur to be greater.
 If slides are more likely/larger, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\text{startzones}}$
\end_inset

 will tend to increase, and if slides are larger, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\text{avalanche}}$
\end_inset

 is surely larger.
 As backcountry travelers, larger and more-likely slides will force us to
 look across larger areas (further uphill) and in more places (increased
 number of potential start zones).
\end_layout

